{"id":"gnash","term":"Gnash","source":"Easton's Bible Dictionary (M.G. Easton, 1897)","html":"<p>Heb. harak, meaning “to grate the teeth”, (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Job 16:9\">Job 16:9</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Psalms 112:10\">Ps. 112:10</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Lamentations 2:16\">Lam. 2:16</a>), denotes rage or sorrow. (See also <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Acts 7:54\">Acts 7:54</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Mark 9:18\">Mark 9:18</a>.)</p>\n\u0000","refs":["Job 16:9","Psalms 112:10","Lamentations 2:16","Acts 7:54","Mark 9:18"]}